A similar monogram is found in (a), a British museum manuscript of the Incendium. 2 This is a long text, and the scribe has drawn a line against the first passage found in the long text, but omitted in the short text, and marked it with a monogram drawn in a similar way to those in the Emmanuel manuscript, but with the three letters combined,

J.G.S. ( ). The scribe must have been acquainted with

the short text in order to make the annotation: or more probably she had a short text at hand, with which she was comparing the British Museum manuscript. The word “ Reclusa ’' seems to have been here loosely used to denote a member of an enclosed community. Joan Sewell was a Brigittine sister of Henry V’s royal abbey of Sion: she was professed in 1500, 3 and the Martiloge of Sion abbey records that she died on July 2, 1532, and was buried among the other sisters “ iuxta gerras‚’' 4——near the screen which shut off part of the chapel. The Brigittine was a double order, and the brothers and sisters at Sion had separate libraries: the catalogue of the brothers' library still exists, and has been published by Miss Bateson.⁵
